http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Washington State K-12 Social Studies Grade Level Expectations

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: The GLEs provide a grade-by-grade sequence of concepts, regional areas and chronological periods based on the framework of the EALRs and their components. Local school districts are not required to follow this exact sequence; districts can reorder them within grade bands (i.e., 3-5, 6-8, and 9-12). However districts are encouraged to consider the mobility of their students and the advantages of following the recommended sequence to ensure that their students have equitable access to all of the skills that build a strong social studies background. The goal of the GLEs is to help teachers and local districts design the scope and sequence of their social studies programs, and to develop lessons and instruction that ensure all students have an opportunity to master the skills and standards the EALRs and GLEs describe.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands key ideals and principles outlined in the Declaration of Independence, including life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness, the U.S. Constitution, including the rule of law, separation of powers, representative government, and popular sovereignty, and the Bill of Rights, including due process and freedom of expression.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how the Declaration of Independence establishes life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness as goals for our nation.
Explains how the Constitution distinguishes popular sovereignty as a principle of our nation.

Examines how the Twenty-sixth Amendment sought to extend democratic ideals.

Applies the ideals of justice and fairness when making choices or decisions in the classroom or on the playground.

Uses the ideal of fairness when sharing classroom supplies and playground equipment.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Applies the key ideal of the public or common good to uphold rights and responsibilities within the context of the community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains what effect following park rules has on the common good.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates the effectiveness of a law or policy by explaining how it promotes ideals.

Critiques how well the legal ban on smoking in public places in Washington State promotes the right to life [RCW 70.160.030].

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates how a public issue is related to constitutional rights and the common good.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Justifies how a position on the issue of censorship relates to freedom of speech.
Justifies how a position on the phrase "under God" in the Pledge of Allegiance relates to freedom of religion.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes the relationship between the actions of people in Washington State and the ideals outlined in the State Constitution.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines the relationship between Washington State citizens' support for Gordon Hirabayashi's resistance to incarceration and the right to "due process" outlined in Article 1, Section 3 of the State Constitution.

Examines the relationship between the implementation of the Bracero Program and the personal rights outlined in Article 1, Section 3 of the State Constitution.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value:
Evaluates efforts to reduce discrepancies between key ideals and reality in the United States including:

  • How key ideals and constitutional principles set forth in fundamental documents relate to public issues.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Judges how well the Fourteenth and Fifteenth Amendments have expanded freedoms for African Americans and other groups in the past and present.
Judges the legacy of the Declaration of Sentiments and Resolutions in Seneca Falls in promoting women's right to own property.
Judges the legacy of the Indian Reorganization Act in promoting the rights of tribal governments.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates how well court decisions and government policies have upheld key ideals and principles in the United States.

Critiques how courts and government policies have supported or failed to support the constitutional right to freedom of speech.
Critiques how well the Supreme Court decision in Parents Involved in Community Schools v. Seattle School Dist. No. 1 upheld the right to equal protection.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates relationships between key ideals and historical and current realities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Judges the relationship between environmental regulations and the constitutional principle of eminent domain.
Judges the relationship between the concept of equal opportunity and the effects of the Individuals with Disabilities Education Improvement Act.
Judges the relationship between the concept of state's rights and the effects of the No Child Left Behind Act.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the purposes, organization, and function of governments, laws, and political systems.
Structure of Government

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Identifies the teacher, principal, vice principal, counselor, and others who make and carry out rules at the school.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the basic organization of government in the community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that cities are governed by mayors and city councils.
Explains that police and judges enforce laws.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains the hierarchy of state government over local government.
Explains that tribal governments are sovereign, separate from state and local governments.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the organization of the United States government.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that the national government is organized into three branches: executive, legislative, and judicial.
Explains who is involved in each of the branches of government.
Explains that the President and the Cabinet are part of the federal executive branch.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands and analyzes the structure, organization, and powers of government at the local, state, and tribal levels including the concept of tribal sovereignty.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains the organization and powers of city and county government.
Explains the organization and powers of the three branches of Washington State government.
Explains the organization and powers of a local tribal government.
Explains the populist features of the Washington State Constitution, including initiative and referendum.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands and analyzes the structure and powers of government at the national level.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines Article 1 of the U.S. Constitution and identifies the powers and responsibilities of the House of Representatives and Senate.
Examines Article 2 of the U.S. Constitution and identifies the powers and responsibilities of the President and his cabinet.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Function of Government
Understands the purpose of rules in the classroom and school.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that classroom rules are important so everyone can learn.
Explains that playground rules are important so everyone is safe.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the basic function of government and laws in the community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that city governments make and enforce laws to support a safe community.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how Senate Bill 5610 promoting salmon recovery became a law in 2005.
Explains how a local tribal council created its code of laws.
Explains how the seatbelt law attempts to solve the problem of injury collisions.
Identifies and explains how the voters of Washington State participated in making the law that banned smoking in public places.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the function of the United States government.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how the legislative branch makes laws.
Explains how the judicial branch judges laws according to the U.S. Constitution.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates the effectiveness of federalism in promoting the common good and protecting individual rights.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands that the U.S. government includes concepts of both a democracy and a republic.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how the U.S. government can be considered a "constitutional democracy" because the people are the ultimate source of authority.
Explains how the U.S. government can be considered a "constitutional republic" because its leaders and officials are elected as representatives of the people.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates the impact of various forms of government on people in the past or present.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes and evaluates the structures of state, tribal, and federal forms of governments by comparing them to those of other governments.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Political Parties
Understands and evaluates how political systems in the United States operate.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Evaluates the political system examining the role of the chair and the caucus in national and state legislative bodies.
Explains the impact of third party candidates on U.S. elections.
Evaluates how interest groups use money to promote their agendas and influence the political system.
Evaluates the effectiveness of current campaign finance laws.
Explains how local tribal governments operate and interact within local, state, and federal governments on issues of environmental and conservation initiatives.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the purposes and organization of international relationships and United States foreign policy.

Examines trade between Minoan and Egyptian societies.
Examines alliances between the Assyrians and the Egyptians.
Examines how Alexander the Great expanded the Macedonian empire through military conquest and cultural assimilation of neighboring societies.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines how the World Trade Organization has affected environmental regulations and employment opportunities in Washington State.
Examines how treaties have affected fishing in Washington State.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes how the United States has interacted with other countries in the past or present.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines how the Dawes Act resulted in loss of land and economic devastation for tribes.
Examines how the U.S. government recruited workers from China to build the Transcontinental Railroad.
Examines how the United States recruited workers from Europe to provide industrial labor.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes the relationships and tensions between national interests and international issues in the world in the past or present.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines the relationship between the United States and Mexico in addressing labor issues.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes and evaluates the causes and effects of U.S. foreign policy on people in the United States and the world in the past or present.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines why the United States policy of the Truman Doctrine was implemented and critiques the costs and benefits for Korea.
Examines why the United States was involved in Vietnam between 1950 and 1975 and critiques the costs and benefits of this policy for the United States and the world.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Evaluates the impact of international agreements on contemporary world issues.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Critiques the advantages and disadvantages of belonging to international organizations, such as the United Nations, or adhering to international agreements, such as the North American Free Trade Agreement.
Judges how the ruling in California v. Cabazon Band of Mission Indians (1987) has affected tribal sovereignty.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands civic involvement.
Civic Involvement
Understands that citizenship and civic involvement in the neighborhood and community are the rights and responsibilities of individuals.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that citizens have the right to live in a safe community.
Explains that citizens have the responsibility to obey the laws of the community.
Explains that citizens have the responsibility to take care of the environment in the community.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands that civic participation involves being informed about public issues and voting in elections.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains that reading the newspaper or watching the news can help a citizen stay informed about public issues.
Explains that attending a town meeting can help a citizen stay informed about public issues.
Explains why voting is a civic duty.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands that civic participation involves being informed about how public issues are related to rights and responsibilities.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how the public issue of censorship is related to the right to freedom of speech.
Explains how the public issue of "under God" in the Pledge of Allegiance is related to the right to freedom of religion.
Explains how the public issue of maintaining public parks is related to the responsibility of paying taxes.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the historical origins of civic involvement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how the male, property-owning citizens of ancient Athens practiced direct democracy.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands the effectiveness of different forms of civic involvement.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains the influence of letters to the editor of the local paper on school funding and instructional resources.
Explains the influence of testimony at public hearings on laws regulating the use of private property.
Explains how lobbying the legislature contributed to the passage of the "Becca Bill."

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes how a position on an issue attempts to balance individual rights and the common good.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Takes a position on federal immigration policy that attempts to balance human rights with national security.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes and evaluates ways of influencing national governments and international organizations to establish or preserve individual rights and/or promote the common good.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Using examples of different groups of people in China, examines instances in which individual rights were denied and the struggles that ensued to establish those rights.
Critiques how private corporations in Africa affect the establishment of individual rights and preservation of the common good.
Critiques the effectiveness of what different groups did to stop the violence in East Timor in the 1990s.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Economics - The student applies understanding of economic concepts and systems to analyze decision-making and the interactions between individuals, households, businesses, governments, and societies.
Understands that people have to make choices between wants and needs and evaluate the outcomes of those choices.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Explains how people's choice of purchasing goods from a large business can result in the loss of smaller businesses.
Explains the costs and benefits that food banks and thrift stores provide for people in the community.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Understands and analyzes the costs and benefits of people's decisions to move and relocate to meet their needs and wants.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines the costs of traveling on the Oregon Trail for pioneers and the benefits they received once they reached their destination.
Examines the effects of the Oregon Trail on tribes living in the Pacific Northwest.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines the reasons why colonists chose to dump tea into the Boston Harbor on December 16, 1773.
Examines reasons why colonists chose to move away from Britain, including needs such as economic opportunities and wants such as freedom of religion.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes the costs and benefits of economic choices made by groups and individuals in the past or present.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines how the Phoenicians' use of finite natural resources forced them to relocate.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes the importance of financial literacy in making economic choices related to spending, saving, and investing.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines the costs and benefits of getting a credit card and accumulating debt.
Examines the pros and cons of buying a Washington State lottery ticket.
Examines how people in Washington State make choices about where to invest their money for the highest return and lowest risk.
Examines how people evaluate advertising when choosing where to spend their money.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes examples of how groups and individuals have considered profit and personal values in making economic choices in the past or present.

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: Examines how the profit motive inspired the entrepreneurship of Levi Strauss, Richard Sears, Alvah Roebuck, Henry Wells, and William G. Fargo during the Gold Rush.
Examines how the personal values of settlers determined what services were established, including saloons and general stores.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes how the costs and benefits of economic choices have shaped events in the world in the past or present.

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Analyzes how economic choices made by groups and individuals in the global economy can impose costs and provide benefits.
